Optical properties of the photocatalysts were investigated by UV–vis DR spectra. As shown in Fig. 5b, the absorption edge of the pure TiO2 is observed at about 400 nm, which is corresponding to the band-gap energy of 3.20 eV. Compared with the pure TiO2, the TiO2/CDs nanocomposites exhibited enhanced absorption in visible region. More importantly, the ternary TiO2/CDs/PANI nanocomposites displayed much more pronounced absorptions in visible light. Thus, the ternary nanocomposites could display improved activity under visible-light illumination. The band gap energy (Eg
                     ) of the prepared samples were estimated using Tauc’s equation αhν=B(hν - Eg
                     )n/2. In this equation, α, ν, and B are absorption coefficient, the light frequency, and proportionality constant, respectively [47]. The value of n depends on the characteristics of the transition in the semiconductor. The Eg
                      values were calculated by extrapolation the linear parts of the curves. As can be seen, the Eg
                      values of the resultant nanocomposites are between 1.50 and 3.20 eV.
